subSection.paragraph:
The thorid shrimp genus 

Lebbeus
White, 1847

are heretofore represented by 74 specific taxa worldwide (
Table 1
), of which vast majority are highly localized (e.g., 
Hayashi 1992
; Komai 
et al
. 2004, 2021; 
Marin 2020
). Discovery of new species is still continuing. The Sea of Okhotsk is one of the hot spot areas of the diversity of the genus in spite of the rather high latitudinal location, from where 16 species have been reported (
Brashnikov 1907
; 
Kobjakova 1936
, 
1937
; 
Urita, 1942
; 
Vinogradov 1950
; 
Zarenkov 1960
; 
Hayashi 1992
; 
Komai 2015
; 

Matsuzaki 
et al
. 2015

; 

Komai 
et al
. 2016

; 

Anosov 
et al
. 2018

; 
Marin 2020
).

DNA barcoding often provides useful genetic information for species delimitation and identification (e.g., 

Costa 
et al
. 2007

). Thus, attempt has been made to sequence the barcoding gene COI and 16S rRNA for the three new species described in this article, as well as three comparative species for which sequences were not available heretofore. Total genomic DNA was extracted from fresh or ethanol-preserved pleopod muscle tissue of specimens, using DNeasy Blood & Tissue Kits (Qiagen, Hilden, 
Germany
) with an elution volume of 100 μl. DNA concentrations were measured and recorded with a NanoDrop Lite spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, DE, 
U.S.A.
). Partial sequences of the mitochondrial COI and 16S rRNA gene were amplified using Tks Gflex DNA polymerase (TaKaRa) following manufacturer instruction. The PCR primers are: LCO1490/HCO2198 (COI; 

Folmer 
et al
. 1994

); 16S-L2 (

Schubart 
et al
. 2002

) and 1472(H2) (
Crandall & Fitzpatrick 1996
) (16S). PCR was carried out with 30 cycles of a 8.03 μl reaction volume containing 2.29 μl sterile distilled water, 3.82 μl 2×Gflex PCR buffer (Takara, Otsu, 
Japan
), 0.38 μl of each primer (5 μM), 0.16 μl of Tks Gflex DNA polymerase (Takara, Otsu, 
Japan
) and 0.7 μl template. The thermal cycle profile after an initial 1 min denaturation at 94°C was as follows: denaturation at 98°C for 10 s, annealing at 50°C for 10 s and extension at 68°C for 10s with the final extension at the same temperature for 7 min. The PCR products were purified using Exo Sap-IT (USB, OH, 
U.S.A.
) to remove redundant dNTPs, primers and nucleotides. Direct sequencing of the purified PCR products was performed with the ABI 3130xl Genetic Analyzer (Life Technologies, CA, 
U.S.
A) and dye-labeled terminators (BigDye terminator v. 1.1; Applied Biosystems, CA, 
U.S.
A). The DNA sequences were edited and assembled by GENETYX-MAC v. 17 (Genetyx, 
Tokyo
, 
Japan
).

Sequences of COI and 16S used in this study are summarised in Table 2 . One COI sequence from each previously known species was randomly selected and downloaded from GenBank database except for
L. polaris
. As shown in previous studies, more than one species are represented in COI sequences referred to
L. polaris
(cf. Marin 2020 ;
Komai et al . 2021
). We selected five sequences corresponding to five putative species, evaluated with genetic divergence, to reduce analytical procedure. The obtained sequences were aligned using ClustalW, as implemented in the MEGA X (
Stecher et al . 2020
) with default parameters. K2P divergences were calculated on MEGA X.

